0.body: I recommend working on these with the other people at your table. We will take breaks to review each problem before moving on to the next one.
0.title: Week 2

1.body: Download and unzip sample_dir.zip . Use the cd command to navigate to your downloads folder and enter the newly unzipped Quinnipiac directory. From the start directory, use a series of cd commands to visit the following directories in order: TH130 LearningCommons CCE030 Quinnipiac (return to the starting directory) Once you're able to visit all of these locations, write down the cd commands you used. Answer the following questions: What's the smallest number of commands you could have used to visit all of these locations? What's the largest number of commands you could have used to visit all of these locations? For a command to count, it must take you closer to the next location you're trying to visit. If you make use of the tab key, how few letters could you type when writing the first cd command to move from Quinnipiac to TH130?
1.title: Exercise 1: Terminal Navigation

2.title: Exercise 2: Exploring Java

3.body: Write the programs in these practice exercises from scratch, and try to avoid looking at and copying from previous examples. It's a little more work, but they're short programs and it'll help you remember how these simplified Java program are structured.
3.title: Week 3

4.body: Write a Java program that prints your QU email address. It only has to print your email, not anyone else's email. Run the program on your terminal to make sure it works.
4.title: Problem 1: Hard-Coded Email

5.body: Pair up with another student for this exercise. Each of you need to figure out the other person's QU email address, and you're not allowed to show or tell each other your email address. Instead, come up with a script that you can follow to ask someone for the information necessary to figure out their QU email. Test the script on each other and make sure it works.
5.title: Problem 2: Email Script

6.body: Write a Java program that prints the user's QU email address. As with problem 2, you can't just ask them for their email and repeat what they tell you. You'll need to prompt the user for information that can be used to determine their QU email, then print that email to the terminal. Your script from problem 2 should help. Remember that this program must print the user's email, and people other than you might use it. When you finish this program, anyone in the classroom should be able to use it to print their email without modifying your code. Have a classmate try running it to make sure it also works for them. Hints: prompt for input with readln("some message in quotes") always store input in a variable you can combine variables with quoted text by placing a plus sign between them, as shown in previous examples
6.title: Problem 3: Variable Email
